{{About|the spiritualist suicide|the British military officer|Thomas Bradford|the Mayor of [[Dallas]]|Tom Bradford}} [[File:The Ogden Standard-Examiner - Ruth Starkweather Doran and Professor Thomas Lynn Bradford - 21 February 1921.png|thumb|Ruth Starkweather Doran and Thomas Lynn Bradford]] '''Thomas Lynn Bradford''' (died February 6, 1921) of [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]], is best known for committing [[suicide]] in an attempt to ascertain the existence of an [[afterlife]] and communicate that information to a living accomplice, Ruth Doran.<ref>{{cite book | authorlink = Mary Roach | first = Mary | last = Roach | title = Spook: Science Tackles the Afterlife | year = 2005 | publisher = W. W. Norton | ISBN = 0-393-05962-6}}</ref> On February 6, 1921, Bradford sealed his apartment in Detroit, blew out the pilot on his heater, and turned on the gas, which was successful in killing him.<ref>{{cite journal | authorlink = Mary Roach | first = Mary | last = Roach | url = https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg19225780.075-the-big-questions-what-happens-after-you-die.html | title = The Big Questions: What happens after you die? | magazine = [[New Scientist]] | issue =2578 |date = 18 November 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite interview | last= Roach |first= Mary |subjectlink= Mary Roach | interviewer=[[Jad Abumrad]] | url = http://www.radiolab.org/blogs/radiolab-blog/2009/aug/10/12-proof/ |title= Proof | work = [[Radiolab]] Podcast Short |date = 10 August 2009}}</ref>
Some weeks earlier, Bradford had sought a fellow spiritualist in a newspaper advertisement and Doran responded. The two agreed "that there was but one way to solve the mystery—two minds properly attuned, one of which must shed its earthly mantle".<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-3445_162-994814/the-afterlife-real-or-imagined/?pageNum=3&tag=contentMain;contentBody | title = The Afterlife: Real Or Imagined? | page = 3 | work = CBS Sunday Morning News | date = October 30, 2005 | first = Sean | last = Alfano}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' ran a follow-up under the headline "Dead Spiritualist Silent."<ref>{{cite news | url = https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F70A1EFD395810738DDDA10894DA405B818EF1D3 |title = DEAD SPIRITUALIST SILENT.; Detroit Woman Awaits Message, but Denies Any Compact. | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | date = February 8, 1921 |page =3 | location = Detroit}}</ref>
