{{Infobox thoroughbred racehorse | horsename = Top Deck | image = | caption = | sire = Equestrian | grandsire = [[Equipoise (horse)|Equipoise]] | dam = River Boat | damsire = Chicaro | sex = [[Stallion]] | foaled = 1945 died 1965 | country = United States | colour = Brown | breeder = [[King Ranch]] | owner = J. B. Ferguson | trainer = | record = unraced | earnings = unraced | race = unraced | awards=unraced | honours = [[American Quarter Horse Hall of Fame]] }}
Unraced as a [[Thoroughbred]], the [[stallion]] '''Top Deck''' (1945–1965) went on to become a famous sire of [[Quarter Horse]]s.
==Life==
Top Deck was foaled in 1945 and was injured as a young [[foal]], preventing a racing career.<ref name=Legends>Close and Simmons ''Legends'' pp. 118–119</ref> His sire was a grandson of [[Man o' War (horse)|Man o' War]] named Equestrian. His dam was a daughter of Chicaro, a horse known for speed at the short distances.<ref name=Pedigree>''[http://www.allbreedpedigree.com/top+deck All Breed Pedigree Database Pedigree of Top Deck]''</ref>
Top Deck died in 1965 in [[Purcell, Oklahoma]].<ref name=Legends/> He was the sire of [[Go Man Go]], Rebel Cause, Top Ladybug, Mighty Deck, Decketta, War Machine and [[Moon Deck (horse)|Moon Deck]].<ref name=Pitzer>Pitzer ''Most Influential Quarter Horse Sires'' pp. 144–145</ref> Two of his sons were inducted into the [[American Quarter Horse Hall of Fame]] – Go Man Go and Moon Deck.<ref name=AQHAHOF>{{cite web |title=Top Deck |url=https://www.aqha.com/museum/hall-of-fame/horses/t/top-deck/ |work= AQHA Hall of Fame |author=American Quarter Horse Association (AQHA) |publisher=American Quarter Horse Association |accessdate=September 2, 2017 }}</ref> He sired 440 Quarter Horse foals, with four AQHA Champions, 219 Race Registers of Merit, twelve Performance Registers of Merit and twenty-one Superior Race Horse awards.<ref name=Legends/> Two of his offspring earned the AQHA Supreme Champion award – Astro Deck and War Machine.<ref name=Mattson>Mattson ''Real American Quarter Horse'' pp. 25, 83</ref> Top Deck was 20 years old when he died in 1965.<ref name=AQHAHOF/>
Top Deck was inducted into the American Quarter Horse Hall of Fame in 1990.<ref name=AQHAHOF/>
